    "body": "**Motivation**\r\nCurrently, freshly added transactions in `private_broadcast` are almost immediately flagged and logged as stale by the `resend-stale` job. \r\n\r\n**The Bug**\r\n`m_transactions` maps a transaction to a `std::vector<SendStatus>`. When `try_emplace` adds a new transaction, this vector is empty. When `GetStale()` runs, `DerivePriority()` evaluates the empty vector and returns a default `Priority` struct where `last_confirmed` evaluates to the Unix Epoch (Jan 1, 1970). The stale checker sees a 50-year-old timestamp and immediately flags it. \r\n\r\n**The Fix**\r\nRather than modifying the transient `Priority` struct or creating a \"Zombie Transaction\" edge case by ignoring transactions with 0 picks, this PR modifies the state container:\r\n* Wraps the `SendStatus` vector in a new `TxState` struct inside `private_broadcast.h`.\r\n* `TxState` automatically captures `time_added` upon emplace.\r\n* `GetStale()` now intelligently checks `p.num_confirmed == 0` to measure age against `time_added` for unconfirmed transactions, falling back to `last_confirmed` once network interaction begins.\r\n\r\n**Additional Polish**\r\n* Applied `const` and uniform initialization `{}` to the updated `GetStale()` loop to align with modern style guidelines.\r\n* Updated `private_broadcast_tests.cpp` to properly mock the passage of time for the new grace period.\r\n* Swapped `BOOST_CHECK_EQUAL` for `BOOST_REQUIRE_EQUAL` in the test suite when evaluating vector sizes to prevent a known out-of-bounds `0x0` memory access violation if the size check fails.",
